## Why Am I Studying Payment Security in a Healthcare Project?

That was my first reaction when I saw today's topic. This is a healthcare GRC project — why does payment card security matter here?

The answer I kept coming back to is this: good security principles do not belong to one industry. PCI DSS was built to protect cardholder data, but the controls it prescribes — encryption, access control, monitoring, vulnerability management, documented policies — are the same controls that protect patient health records. Studying how a different industry solved a similar problem turned out to be one of the more useful exercises so far in this challenge.

---

## What I Worked On Today

**PCI DSS** stands for Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard. It is not a law — it is an industry standard created by major credit card companies including Visa, Mastercard, and American Express. Any organization that processes, stores, or transmits cardholder data must comply with it or risk losing the ability to accept card payments.

What makes PCI DSS interesting compared to something like HIPAA is how prescriptive it is. HIPAA uses language like "reasonable and appropriate" and gives organizations flexibility in how they meet requirements. PCI DSS is much more specific — it tells you exactly what to do, how to do it, and how to prove you did it. There is less room for interpretation, which can feel rigid but also removes a lot of ambiguity for organizations that are just starting to build their security programs.

PCI DSS organizes its requirements into 12 core areas. Rather than listing all 12, I want to focus on the ones that felt most directly relevant to what I am building with OpenMRS:

**Network Security** — Build and maintain secure network configurations, use firewalls, and never use vendor-supplied default passwords. For OpenMRS on AWS this means properly configured security groups, a web application firewall, and making sure no default credentials are left in place on any component.

**Data Protection** — Encrypt sensitive data at rest and in transit. For OpenMRS this is directly parallel to HIPAA's encryption requirements — patient records in the database should be encrypted, and all web traffic should run over HTTPS.

**Vulnerability Management** — Keep systems patched and protected from malware. An unpatched OpenMRS server is a known risk, and PCI DSS makes patching a formal requirement rather than something that happens when time allows.

**Access Control** — Enforce least privilege, use unique accounts for every user, and restrict physical access to systems. Role-based access control in OpenMRS, combined with MFA, directly satisfies this principle.

**Monitoring and Testing** — Log all access to sensitive data, review those logs regularly, and test security controls through vulnerability scans and penetration testing. This one stood out to me the most.

**Security Policies** — Maintain documented security policies and train staff. Again — the human and process layer showing up alongside the technical one.

