## What Actually Clicked for Me

The requirement that stood out most today was **Requirement 10 — Track and Monitor All Access**.

The core idea is simple: you cannot protect what you do not monitor. Every access to sensitive data should be logged — who accessed it, when, from where, and what they did. Those logs need to be reviewed regularly, not just stored and forgotten.

In the context of OpenMRS, this is not just a PCI DSS principle — it is also a HIPAA requirement under the audit controls standard (§164.312(b)). The two frameworks are pointing at the same thing from different directions: if a patient's records are accessed inappropriately, you need to be able to detect it, investigate it, and respond to it. That only happens if logging is in place and someone is actually looking at the logs.

What clicked for me is that monitoring is often treated as optional or secondary — something you set up "when there is time." Both PCI DSS and HIPAA treat it as foundational. That reframing matters.

The other thing I found genuinely interesting today was the difference between prescriptive and flexible frameworks. PCI DSS tells you exactly what to do. HIPAA and NIST give you principles and ask you to apply them to your context. Neither approach is universally better — prescriptive frameworks reduce ambiguity and are easier to audit, while flexible frameworks encourage organizations to think about their actual risk environment rather than just checking boxes. As I go deeper into this project I am starting to think the best real-world programs probably combine both: use prescriptive requirements as a baseline, then build a more mature risk-driven program on top.

