## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2013 Target data breach** — one of the most well-known payment security failures in history. Attackers stole the credit and debit card data of approximately 40 million customers during the holiday shopping season. The breach caused enormous financial and reputational damage and ultimately led to the resignation of Target's CEO.

What made this case relevant to today's topic is how it happened. Attackers gained access through a third-party HVAC vendor that had network access to Target's systems. Once inside, they moved laterally and eventually reached the point-of-sale systems where card data was being processed.

Target was PCI DSS compliant at the time of the breach. That fact stopped me when I read it. A company that had passed a PCI DSS audit was still breached in a significant way. What went wrong? Investigators found that monitoring alerts had actually fired during the attack — but they were not acted on in time. The controls existed. The logs existed. The detection existed. But the response process was not mature enough to turn that detection into action before serious damage was done.

That is a sobering reminder of something I first encountered on Day 4: compliance is the floor, not the ceiling. Meeting the requirements is necessary but not sufficient. The Target breach showed that you can check every box and still be vulnerable if the human and process layers are not working alongside the technical ones.

