## Connecting PCI DSS Back to OpenMRS

Thinking about how PCI DSS principles apply to an OpenMRS deployment on AWS, here is the mapping I worked through:

| PCI DSS Principle | OpenMRS Application |
|---|---|
| Secure network configuration | AWS security groups, WAF, no default credentials |
| Encrypt sensitive data | Database encryption at rest, HTTPS for all web traffic |
| Patch and update systems | Regular patching of OpenMRS, OS, and dependencies |
| Enforce access control | Role-based access, MFA for admin accounts, unique user IDs |
| Monitor and log access | AWS CloudTrail, OpenMRS audit logs, regular log reviews |
| Maintain security policies | Documented access control and incident response policies |

Going through that mapping reinforced something I have been noticing throughout this first week: the same core controls keep appearing across every framework. Encrypt data. Control access. Monitor what is happening. Keep systems patched. Train people. Document your decisions. The frameworks differ in structure and emphasis — but the underlying security fundamentals are remarkably consistent.

